Add Day 11 exercise 1.2 tester from Nathan

From pair programming.

Allow accessing single values in Day9 HashTable

Re-write the HashTable to use a Stack to store the multiple values associated with each key, making it easy to access or remove just the most-recently added value.

Rename Day9 GenericStack to NumberStack

The exercise asks for a polymorphic stack restricted to Numbers, so NumberStack is a more accurate name. It also frees up GenericStack as a name for a fully generic stack I can use to implement the HashTable.
A more generic solution for Day 9 exercise 1

Expose multiple values as Iterator in HashTable

HashTable returns multiple values for a given key, so needs to return some collection of values. It's better to use an interface, rather than expose a specific, concrete collection class as the return value of get. Here, I return Iterator, although perhaps there is a better interface (e.g. Collection or Iterable) in the Java standard library.

Use an internal class in GenericStack

Nothing other than GenericStack needs to use the GenericStackNode, so make it a private class within GenericStack.

Make DoublyLinkedList implement Iterator interface

I'd already added a next() method to DoublyLinkedList. This commit adds the relevant features to allow the DoublyLinkedList to be treated as a Java Iterator.

(It's probably not a good idea to have the class itself be an iterator - what if two bits of code want to iterate over the list at the same time - but it's simply for this illustration).

Add solution for Day 9 exercise 4

As the exercise involves creating a subclass of DoublyLinkedList that alters the way elements are added to the list, I altered the visibility of some fields in DoublyLinkedList to protected.

Add solution for Day 9 exercise 2.5

Note that this code intentionally reports an error at runtime, as it attempts to cast a MobilePhone object to a SmartPhone object.

Add code for Day 9 exercise 2.2

Note that this code intentionally does not work, illustrating that  you cannot call methods that are only defined on subclass when it has been upcast.

Add more animals

Adds Cat, Crocodile, and Dog.

Change Response to be an interface

The different responses don't seem to need an shared behaviour, so there's no strong reason to make them descend from a common class. Also, it makes more sense for the default response to be a separate class called DefaultResponse.

The "dump" method was useful for debugging the ArrayPersonQueue implementation, but is probably not in general useful for other implementations, so should not be part of the interface (the method still exists on the ArrayPersonQueue class, in case it is still useful there).
